1
00:00:01,666 --> 00:00:04,866
Instant messaging is now a major part of everyday communication

2
00:00:05,400 --> 00:00:08,000
and voice typing is becoming more and more common

3
00:00:08,066 --> 00:00:10,200
common because it is quick and convenient

4
00:00:10,600 --> 00:00:13,266
But once spoken language is turned into plain text

5
00:00:13,633 --> 00:00:15,833
a lot of emotional information disappears

6
00:00:16,466 --> 00:00:17,466
The words remain

7
00:00:17,866 --> 00:00:19,466
but important cues like tone

8
00:00:19,800 --> 00:00:20,366
pitch

9
00:00:20,366 --> 00:00:23,366
cadence and emotional nuance are filtered out

10
00:00:23,600 --> 00:00:25,633
This motivated us to ask whether voice

11
00:00:25,633 --> 00:00:27,100
typing could be more expressive

12
00:00:27,800 --> 00:00:29,233
Instead of only being accurate

13
00:00:29,833 --> 00:00:31,066
To think about this

14
00:00:31,400 --> 00:00:33,633
we looked at two lines of previous work

15
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:35,100
On one side

16
00:00:35,600 --> 00:00:38,566
research on voice typing has made speech input efficient

17
00:00:38,900 --> 00:00:40,433
usable and editable

18
00:00:40,866 --> 00:00:44,466
But it usually treats the transcript as plain lexical content

19
00:00:45,066 --> 00:00:46,000
On the other side

20
00:00:46,366 --> 00:00:48,300
research on kinetic typography and

21
00:00:48,300 --> 00:00:50,433
effective captions has shown that

22
00:00:50,433 --> 00:00:52,800
 text can visually express tone and emotion

23
00:00:53,366 --> 00:00:56,566
But these systems are often manually authored or

24
00:00:56,566 --> 00:00:58,866
designed for passive viewing scenarios like

25
00:00:58,866 --> 00:00:59,666
storytelling

26
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:01,266
videos or captioning

27
00:01:01,700 --> 00:01:04,000
rather than for real time instant messaging

28
00:01:04,600 --> 00:01:06,633
That is why we ask the following question

29
00:01:07,200 --> 00:01:09,966
How can we translate vocal emotion into kinetic

30
00:01:09,966 --> 00:01:13,300
typography to enhance expressiveness in instant messaging

31
00:01:13,533 --> 00:01:15,700
 without compromising legibility

32
00:01:16,233 --> 00:01:18,600
and which visual strategies work best

33
00:01:19,100 --> 00:01:20,166
To address this

34
00:01:20,433 --> 00:01:22,600
we first conducted a co design study

35
00:01:23,033 --> 00:01:25,500
then derived a design space with three dimensions

36
00:01:26,033 --> 00:01:26,833
geometry

37
00:01:26,833 --> 00:01:27,700
texture and motion

38
00:01:28,266 --> 00:01:31,766
and finally built emotype-zero as a research probe 

39
00:01:31,766 --> 00:01:35,366
to explore these ideas in realistic messaging scenarios

40
00:01:36,100 --> 00:01:39,766
Our first step was a co design workshop with nine participants

41
00:01:40,266 --> 00:01:43,433
We recruited long term voice typing users and

42
00:01:43,433 --> 00:01:45,600
asked them to reflect on how emotional speech

43
00:01:45,600 --> 00:01:47,666
could be represented visually in text

44
00:01:48,466 --> 00:01:50,233
Participants reviewed examples

45
00:01:50,800 --> 00:01:53,066
listened to emotionally varied audio clips

46
00:01:53,366 --> 00:01:55,666
and then created their own expressive text

47
00:01:55,666 --> 00:01:58,000
concepts through sketching and discussion

48
00:01:58,766 --> 00:02:00,433
We documented the workshop

49
00:02:00,833 --> 00:02:02,400
collected the design artifacts

50
00:02:02,833 --> 00:02:05,000
and analyzed the recurring relationships

51
00:02:05,066 --> 00:02:07,233
between vocal cues and visual expression

52
00:02:07,866 --> 00:02:10,200
That analysis led directly to our next

53
00:02:10,200 --> 00:02:13,066
contribution a structured design space

54
00:02:13,100 --> 00:02:15,233
for emotional kinetic typography

55
00:02:15,466 --> 00:02:17,233
The first dimension is geometry

56
00:02:17,566 --> 00:02:19,466
which changes the shape of the text

57
00:02:19,900 --> 00:02:21,666
The second is texture

58
00:02:21,900 --> 00:02:24,033
which adds subtle emotional cues

59
00:02:24,166 --> 00:02:26,000
through effects like color and glow

60
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:27,800
The third is motion

61
00:02:28,666 --> 00:02:30,633
which uses movements such as pulse

62
00:02:30,700 --> 00:02:33,566
jitter and drift to reflect speech emotion

63
00:02:34,466 --> 00:02:35,166
together

64
00:02:35,166 --> 00:02:37,866
they form a design space for expressive but still

65
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:42,466
Based on this design space

66
00:02:42,933 --> 00:02:45,066
we then developed emotype-zero to

67
00:02:45,266 --> 00:02:47,166
explore how these strategies could be

68
00:02:47,166 --> 00:02:49,600
implemented and evaluated in practice

69
00:02:50,366 --> 00:02:54,000
Emotype transforms spoken input into emotionally

70
00:02:54,166 --> 00:02:57,333
expressive kinetic typography by analyzing speech

71
00:02:57,366 --> 00:02:59,933
emotion and adapting fonts in real time

72
00:03:00,633 --> 00:03:01,366
Technically

73
00:03:01,366 --> 00:03:03,566
it is a web based messaging prototype

74
00:03:04,066 --> 00:03:06,166
the user speaks into the chat interface

75
00:03:06,566 --> 00:03:08,400
the system captures the audio

76
00:03:08,766 --> 00:03:10,533
analyzes the emotion in the speech

77
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:13,333
and then uses that information to generate

78
00:03:13,433 --> 00:03:15,800
expressive typography in the final text message

79
00:03:16,466 --> 00:03:18,033
From the user's perspective

80
00:03:18,366 --> 00:03:20,166
the interaction is also simple

81
00:03:20,766 --> 00:03:21,533
tap

82
00:03:21,533 --> 00:03:24,066
speak and view the expressive result

83
00:03:24,766 --> 00:03:25,566
Here

84
00:03:25,566 --> 00:03:28,000
we show how emotype-zero works in a

85
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:29,666
real world messaging scenario

86
00:03:29,766 --> 00:03:31,266
I'm glad to see you again

87
00:03:31,566 --> 00:03:32,366
oh my God

88
00:03:32,600 --> 00:03:33,400
so happy

89
00:03:33,933 --> 00:03:35,366
Building on the previous example

90
00:03:35,866 --> 00:03:38,366
emotype-zero can distinguish both the type

91
00:03:38,566 --> 00:03:40,433
and the intensity of speech emotion

92
00:03:41,066 --> 00:03:43,466
and reflect these differences through

93
00:03:43,566 --> 00:03:46,133
adaptive typography in everyday communication

94
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:48,633
With this prototype in place

95
00:03:49,033 --> 00:03:52,400
we then moved on to evaluate how users responded to

96
00:03:52,400 --> 00:03:54,800
these different expressive rendering strategies

97
00:03:55,533 --> 00:03:55,733
so

98
00:03:55,733 --> 00:03:58,633
we conducted a user study with 25 participants

99
00:03:59,166 --> 00:04:00,966
they first completed scripted tasks

100
00:04:01,200 --> 00:04:02,633
where they spoke prepared lines

101
00:04:02,633 --> 00:04:03,766
with different emotions

102
00:04:04,033 --> 00:04:05,500
and then a freestyle task

103
00:04:05,833 --> 00:04:08,500
where they created more natural messages of their own

104
00:04:08,833 --> 00:04:09,633
After that

105
00:04:09,700 --> 00:04:11,166
they ranked the six modes

106
00:04:11,266 --> 00:04:13,266
and participated in an interview

107
00:04:13,700 --> 00:04:15,800
The result showed a clear tradeoff

108
00:04:16,200 --> 00:04:18,900
Geometry emerged as the most preferred overall

109
00:04:19,100 --> 00:04:20,633
because it balanced emotional

110
00:04:20,633 --> 00:04:22,366
clarity with reading stability

111
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:24,000
In contrast

112
00:04:24,433 --> 00:04:27,166
motion and combo were often seen as more expressive

113
00:04:27,566 --> 00:04:29,666
but also harder to read when the

114
00:04:29,666 --> 00:04:30,900
effects became too strong

115
00:04:31,766 --> 00:04:34,166
Participants also reported that expressive

116
00:04:34,166 --> 00:04:36,900
typography helped them better understand tone

117
00:04:37,466 --> 00:04:39,400
and many said they would be willing to use

118
00:04:39,400 --> 00:04:41,633
this kind of system in daily messaging

119
00:04:42,400 --> 00:04:43,200
From this

120
00:04:43,466 --> 00:04:45,566
we identified three main findings

121
00:04:46,200 --> 00:04:47,000
First

122
00:04:47,300 --> 00:04:49,200
motion is especially effective for

123
00:04:49,200 --> 00:04:50,666
expressing emotional arousal

124
00:04:51,066 --> 00:04:53,233
but too much movement can hurt readability

125
00:04:54,100 --> 00:04:54,900
Second

126
00:04:55,100 --> 00:04:56,866
users prefer geometry as a

127
00:04:56,866 --> 00:04:58,866
practical default for everyday use

128
00:04:59,266 --> 00:05:01,633
while stronger dynamic effects are better

129
00:05:01,633 --> 00:05:03,500
reserved for high arousal messages

130
00:05:04,266 --> 00:05:05,066
Third

131
00:05:05,100 --> 00:05:07,566
kinetic typography plays an important role in

132
00:05:07,566 --> 00:05:10,466
restoring emotion in speech to text communication

133
00:05:11,033 --> 00:05:13,200
helping plain transcription become a richer

134
00:05:13,200 --> 00:05:15,100
and more socially meaningful experience

135
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:17,000
In conclusion

136
00:05:17,466 --> 00:05:20,233
emotype-zero shows that speech emotion can be

137
00:05:20,233 --> 00:05:24,233
meaningfully restored in text through adaptive typography

138
00:05:24,766 --> 00:05:26,433
rather than treating speech to text

139
00:05:26,433 --> 00:05:28,166
as plain transcription only

140
00:05:28,666 --> 00:05:30,600
Our work suggests that voice typed

141
00:05:30,633 --> 00:05:33,566
messages can also preserve emotional intent

142
00:05:34,266 --> 00:05:36,600
This has important implications for making

143
00:05:36,633 --> 00:05:38,766
voice to text messaging more expressive

144
00:05:39,466 --> 00:05:41,100
reducing emotional ambiguity

145
00:05:41,466 --> 00:05:44,666
and inspiring new effective and accessible interfaces

146
00:05:45,633 --> 00:05:46,700
In future work

147
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:50,433
we plan to explore lower latency on device models

148
00:05:50,666 --> 00:05:53,166
more personalized control of visual intensity

149
00:05:53,566 --> 00:05:56,466
and accessibility support for DHH users

150
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:59,266
we hope this work contributes to more

151
00:05:59,300 --> 00:06:01,666
expressive human centered text communication

152
00:06:02,266 --> 00:06:03,600
Thank you very much for watching

153
00:02:37,766 --> 00:02:40,066
readable typography in everyday messaging

